2022 Setup Changes in Review

It’s officially 2023! And while my Cabin Fever setup upgrade isn’t complete, I wanted to take a moment to go over the progress thus far to see how the little changes add up.

We started with the boom arm. I replaced the old wobbly boom arm with the Kensington boom arm. It’s very sturdy, it has a nice aesthetic, and the cable management rail is great.

Then we replaced the Dell Monitor stands with the Kensington Dual Monitor Arm. This freed up a ton of space on the desk shelf, and created a much cleaner look, as well as contributed a bit to the ergonomics and make it really easy to adjust them.

From there we replaced the old desk shelf for the updated Grovemade desk shelf, added the MacBook dock, and the Kensington Thunderbolt 3 Dual 4K dock for much better I/O and more access to USB ports. We also replaced the leather mouse pad for a full matte desk pad that can hold both the keyboard and the mouse.

It’s already looking so much cleaner and more efficient, and if I had to choose my favorite change thus far, it’d be the boom arm and the MacBook dock (it’s so much easier to dock in and out than what I was doing before).

I’m excited to continue the progress, but I’m attending CES this week so I don’t think I’ll be able to get it done before I leave. Nevertheless, stay tuned! 🙌

#ad You don’t always need a higher speed plan, sometimes your router just isn’t equipped to handle your devices and network usage.

Fun fact, Netflix recommends 5mbp/s for Full HD streaming. Now imagine you have a 500mbps connection. That means you could stream to 100 devices to max out your bandwidth. Obviously this is a loose example, but you get the point.

Most of the time, we don’t actually need a speed upgrade, we need a router upgrade. And when working from home, this is especially important.

The @ArubaSMB Instant On AP22 provides a great set of features for small businesses or those that work from home, including:

Wi-Fi 6 
MU-MIMO 
Smart Mesh Wi-Fi support
Built-in Wi-Fi router/gateway functionality
Bluetooth
Secure Guest Wi-Fi with a simple setup
And an easy app for setup and management

If you’re having issues with your WiFi, it might be time to go ahead and upgrade your router.

After 3 months of using my Boox Note Air2 Plus e-ink tablet here’s my thoughts.

In short, I love it.

The battery life is amazing, I can use it for days (weeks even) without needing to charge it. 

The writing experience is so smooth and feels great, it's definitely an upgrade compared to writing on my iPad. The e-ink display is so easy on my eyes and the backlight is perfect for reading in the evening.

Having a dedicated e-ink tablet is a completely different experience compared to using an iPad. If you have the money, I highly recommend investing in one. I use my Boox Note for journaling, reading books, and taking notes. It's just so convenient to have everything in one place.

However, there are a few things I wish were better. The responsiveness of the pen could be faster and the backlight could be more consistent. It seems that the dual-tone is split by screen sides, which can be a bit distracting. Despite these small issues, I still think the Boox Note Air2 Plus is an excellent e-ink tablet and I would definitely recommend it.

Late last year into early this year I started to feel weird sensations in my heart. After using my Apple Watch ECG function and cross referencing the results with my doctor, it was determined that I was experiencing frequent PVC’s, otherwise known as Premature Ventricular Contractions or in plain terms, my heart was skipping a beat.

It became clear that this was due to excess caffeine and alcohol. My doctor recommended I cut back dramatically on both and so I did. I had to become very clear about what I was drinking and how often.

One of the things that I have recently grown to love aside from my coffee addiciton is energy drinks. And unfortunately, most of them are absolutely PACKED with caffeine which meant I couldn’t drink them often anymore.

I got the chance to try Juvee after their GM Sam sent out a case to me. I was really excited to try it, not only because of the hype but also because it contained significantly less caffeine per can than some of the others I was used to drinking. And of course it’s low in calories and contains 0 sugar.

And it didn’t disappoint. The flavor is great, not extremely potent but more gentle. And the caffeine content is a healthy one, slightly more than a cup of coffee. So it’s enough to give me a decent boost, but not too much to be a problem for me.

Of course I still have to be cautious and continue to monitor my situation under the supervision of my doctor, but I’m really glad I was able to find something that’s a bit more gentle on my heart! Stoked to try some of their other flavors!

A Luxury Webcam? 📷 Does it live up to its hype? 👇

I recently got my hands on the Opal C1, a webcam claiming DSLR-like quality and sporting a f/1.8 aperture. Finished with aluminum housing, there’s definitely no doubt that this is one of the best looking webcams out there.

But can it live up to it’s own hype?

Well, I’ve been using it the past week and there’s some good, and some bad:

The Bad:
First, it’s Mac specific. If you have a PC, it might work but you won’t be able to control it using the Opal Composer software. And even on Mac, the software was extremely buggy for me. And they recently disabled some already existing features it had on Intel-based Macs citing GPU resource issues. So even if you have a Mac, if it’s an Intel one you won’t get full functionality.

And as far as the image quality itself? It’s good, but it’s not amazing. There’s a ton of noise in the image. And I have to say, I think the Razer Kiyo Pro Ultra produces a better, sharper image. However, it is decent. I’ll give it that.

The Good:
Well, that’s where I’m struggling. It’s a decent quality webcam. But it’s going to run you $250. And with the limitations of it being Mac-only, only fully supporting Apple Silicon, with the software performing buggy at best and the image containing a ton of noise… I’m not entirely sure I can justify it.

I’m going to spend some more time with it and give you a follow up soon!

4 Months Later With The ROG Ally 👇

Four months ago, I welcomed the ROG Ally into my gaming arsenal, and I’m sharing my in-depth experience with this portable gaming device. 🕹️

At first glance, the ROG Ally is an impressive piece of tech. It delivers solid performance in a variety of games, making it a reliable choice for on-the-go gaming sessions. The sleek design and robust build quality make it stand out, and its portability is a definite plus.

However, as the months rolled on, I discovered a few limitations that are worth noting. While it excels in some games, it falls short in others (Madden 24 is a big one) which highlights that it's not a complete replacement for a full-fledged gaming PC or laptop. If you're into graphics-intensive titles or esports games that demand high frame rates, you might find it struggling to keep up.

The biggest hurdle for me has been the battery life. It's no secret that gaming laptops often face challenges in this department, and the ROG Ally is no exception. If you're planning an extended gaming session away from an outlet, you'll want to keep a close eye on that battery indicator.

Despite these limitations, the ROG Ally shines in certain scenarios. It's fantastic as a standalone device when you need quick gaming fixes while traveling or in situations where a full gaming rig isn't practical. The convenience of having a capable gaming machine at your fingertips cannot be overstated.

The Ally has been a valuable addition to my gaming setup, but it comes with its fair share of pros and cons. It's a dependable choice for gaming on the go, but its performance varies depending on the title. Just remember, it's not a full gaming PC replacement, and the battery life may leave you wanting more. 🎮

Did you have a productive week? 🤨

Last week I posted a Reel about how I stay on track to complete my to-do lists for the day and get everything done that I need to for the week.

In case you missed it, here's the process that works for me 👇

1. Start with a digital to-do list. This includes EVERYTHING that needs to get done.
2. Break that to-do list down into 3 core tasks that MUST get done today and write them down. Non-negotiable tasks that move the needle forward for the overall goal. This can be different for different people.
3. As you are completing your core 3 tasks, make sure to mark them off. It's a small dopamine hit.
4. If you can, try to do things that boost your mood/motivation. I like to play music when I'm working, but unfortunately I cannot always do that especially when I'm editing videos. However when I'm doing administrative tasks, I'm usually blasting my speakers with some music.
5. As long as your core 3 task list is complete at the end of the day, that day is a success no matter what your overall to-do list looks like.

Bonus Tip: Figure out if there's anything on your big to-do list that can be delegated. If so, delegate it. Sometimes we put things on our list that don't belong there.

Hope these tips help you, but in the meantime... It's the freaking weekend! I'm away in the mountains right now 🏔️ so I hope you're enjoying your weekend too!

When I saw this unveiled at the Microsoft Event, I was impressed but skeptical it could replace my workstation… but after using it instead of my Macbook Pro, I’m impressed. 

First of all the hardware is very capable. And while I do think Apple Silicon is a superior architecture to what Intel is currently producing... The combination of the latest Intel Processors with NVIDIA’s 4060 Laptop GPU produces a powerful combination with decent thermals and power consumption. 

Initially I thought the device was underpowered. I would dock it and get laggy performance and I wasn’t sure if I was hitting the limits, or if the lower PD from my TB4 dock was causing the issue. But once I switched my power profile in Windows, I saw a huge spike in performance. Also, the Surface is able to handle most games I throw at it on a blend between medium and high settings (with some on occassion being set to low).

Battery life is excellent for day-to-day tasks, the touchscreen with a pen makes me forget about my iPad for photo editing. While I miss iMessage and AirDrop, Intel Unison works well for file transfers and notifications. Wish Windows would take some notes for Phone Link, I found it inferior.

Do I think this is the most powerful laptop out there? No. Do I think this is for everyone? Also, no.

It might not be the most powerful laptop for everyone, but for creators, it’s a compelling choice with creative capabilities, touch screen, and portable gaming in an attractive form factor. Windows 11 is a HUGE step in the right direction, and competition with Apple Silicon  is on the horizon with the latest ARM processors.

This Surface Laptop Studio 2 is now my permanent PC, and I don’t plan on replacing it anytime soon.

ONE command to automate your ENTIRE bedtime routine 🛌

This is especially great as you continue to add more smart accessories as the possibilities become limitless. Here’s how:

1. Create a Siri shortcut and name it the command
2. Add any smart home actions (turn off lights, etc)
3. Set focus mode to sleep 💤 
4. Ask for input and set it to date
5. Get date from that command
6. Create alarm and use the variable date
7. Speak your closing text

Now this will create duplicate alarms if the time already exists but only one goes off. Plus you can always tell Siri to delete all alarms for some clean up.

Hope this helps! Sleep tight! 😴
